b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe15068.htm)  [Next](sbe15070.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B002DEMBWG/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n[![](../../img/tn_hin.jpg)](index.htm)  \n_The Upanishads, Part 2 (SBE15)_ , by Max Muller, [1879], at sacred-texts.com\n\n* * *\n\n### SIXTH BR\xc3\x82HMA _N_ A 3.\n\n1\\. Then Gargi Va _k_ aknavi asked. 'Ya _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ avalkya,' she said,\n'everything here is woven, like warp and woof, in water. What then is that in\nwhich water is woven, like warp and woof?'\n\n'In air, O Gargi,' he replied.\n\n'In what then is air woven, like warp and woof?'\n\n'In the worlds of the sky, O Gargi, 'he replied.\n\n'In what then are the worlds of the sky woven, like warp and woof?'\n\n'In the worlds of the Gandharvas, O Gargi,' he replied.\n\np. 131\n\n'In what then are the worlds of the Gandharvas woven, like warp and woof?'\n\n'In the worlds of \xc3\x82ditya (sun), O Gargi,' he replied.\n\n'In what then are the worlds of \xc3\x82ditya (sun) woven, like warp and woof?'\n\n'In the worlds of _K_ andra (moon), O Gargi,' he replied.\n\n'In what then are the worlds of _K_ andra (moon) woven, like warp and woof?'\n\n, In the worlds of the Nakshatras (stars), O Gargi,' he replied.\n\n'In what then are the worlds of the Nakshatras (stars) woven, like warp and\nwoof?'\n\n'In the worlds of the Devas (gods), O Gargi,' he replied.\n\n'In what then are the worlds of the Devas (gods) woven, like warp and woof?'\n\n'In the worlds of Indra, O Gargi,' he replied.\n\n'In what then are the worlds of Indra woven, like warp and woof?'\n\n'In the worlds of Pra _g_ apati, O Gargi,' he replied.\n\n'In what then are the worlds of Pra _g_ apati woven, like warp and woof?'\n\n'In the worlds of Brahman, O Gargi,' he replied.\n\n'In what then are the worlds of Brahman woven, like warp and woof?'\n\nYa _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ avalkya said: 'O Gargi, Do not ask too much, lest thy head should\nfall off. Thou askest too much about a deity about which we are not to ask too\nmuch 1. Do not ask too much, O Gargi.' After that Gargi Va _k_ aknavi held her\npeace.\n\n* * *\n\n### Footnotes\n\n[130:3](sbe15069.htm#fr_408) Madhyandina text, p. 1072.\n\n[131:1](sbe15069.htm#fr_409) According to the commentator questions about\nBrahman are to be answered from the Scriptures only, and not to be settled by\nargument.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: III, 7](sbe15070.htm)\n\n"